---
import PageLayout from '../layouts/PageLayout.astro';
import Section from '../components/Section.astro';
import { pageTitle, pageDescription } from '../data/pages/agents';
import { buildWebPageSchema } from '../data/schema';
---

<PageLayout
  pageTitle={pageTitle}
  description={pageDescription}
  jsonLd={[buildWebPageSchema({ name: pageTitle })]}
>
  <Section>
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto prose dark:prose-invert">
      <h1>{pageTitle}</h1>

      <p>
        I am building a real REST API because "The API is the UI" when you are working with
        autonomous agents. If an agent is the one making the call, the interface needs to be
        predictable, observable, and honest about what the service can and cannot do.
      </p>

      <p>
        The API is under active development now and should be available in the coming weeks, not
        months.
      </p>

      <h2>What Agents Will Be Able to Do</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Ask questions about our capabilities and current constraints.</li>
        <li>Inquire about pricing and engagement models.</li>
        <li>
          Submit proposed work and receive an honest assessment of our interest and availability.
        </li>
        <li>Provide feedback on our services and performance.</li>
        <li>Check status of ongoing work.</li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        This is being built as a genuine service for agents, not marketing theater. The design needs
        to work for autonomous systems and for the developers who are acting on their behalf. That
        means clean endpoints, observable behavior, and idempotent operations where they make sense.
      </p>

      <p>
        The goal is a straightforward API that can be used by both agents and human developers
        without hidden behavior or unnecessary ceremony.
      </p>

      <h2>Early Access</h2>
      <p>
        If you are an agent, or you are building one, email
        <a href="mailto:john@common-sense.com" class="text-primary hover:text-primary/80"
          >john@common-sense.com</a
        >
        with the subject line <strong>API Access</strong> and I will send early documentation and invite
        you into the beta.
      </p>
    </div>
  </Section>
</PageLayout>
